  <mainDescription>&lt;h3>&#xD;
    AGR: Services architecture&#xD;
&lt;/h3>&#xD;
&lt;p>&#xD;
    An initial Services Architecture for the AGR business case (see figure 12) was defined using the methodology guidelines&#xD;
    by applying the Value Delivery Model to Business SoaML mapping rules, i.e., mapping participants and grouping&#xD;
    deliverable flows into service contracts.&#xD;
&lt;/p>&#xD;
&lt;p>&#xD;
    &lt;img alt=&quot;&quot; src=&quot;resources/agr_services_architecture_example.png&quot; width=&quot;600&quot; height=&quot;396&quot; />&#xD;
&lt;/p>&#xD;
&lt;p>&#xD;
    &lt;strong>Figure 12: Initial Services Architecture for the AGR business case&lt;br />&#xD;
    &lt;/strong>&lt;br />&#xD;
    The initial Services Architecture identifies all participants and one service contract for each of the collaborations&#xD;
    between two specific participants. This architecture describes a top-level view of how independent participants work&#xD;
    together. The focal point of the analysis is on the Infrastructure Provider fulfilled by Vlastuin. Figure 13 shows a&#xD;
    filtered participant view focusing on the Infrastructure Provider and its service contracts.&#xD;
&lt;/p>&#xD;
&lt;img alt=&quot;&quot; src=&quot;resources/agr_services_architecture_example2.png&quot; width=&quot;347&quot; height=&quot;277&quot; />&lt;br />&#xD;
&lt;p>&#xD;
    &lt;strong>Figure 13: Infrastructure Provider view of the Services Architecture&lt;/strong>&#xD;
&lt;/p>&#xD;
&lt;p>&#xD;
    The Infrastructure Provider view was defined using a top-down approach resulting from applying mapping rules on the&#xD;
    Value Delivery Model. In order to detail the identified Service Contracts we used both a top-down approach looking at&#xD;
    the business processes and a bottom-up approach looking at technical Web Services.&#xD;
&lt;/p></mainDescription>
</org.eclipse.epf.uma:GuidanceDescription>
